 this original, topical book, leading experts from eight countries examine how early education and care is organised, funded and regulated in their countries. Bringing together recent statistical evidence, the book gives an up-to-date picture of access to services by different groups, providing rich insights on how policies play out in practice, and the extent to which they help or hinder disadvantaged children to receive high quality provision. An equal start? reveals the common tensions and complexities countries face in ensuring that early education and care is affordable, accessible and of high quality. Its critical examination of the potential for better policies ensures that An equal start? will be of interest to academic readers as well as policy makers and practitioners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChild development. 0aEarly childhood education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAkgündüz, Yusuf Emre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrennan, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllingsæter, Anne Lise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagnani, Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenec, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGambaro, Ludovica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGambaro, Ludovica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMagnuson, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMay, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOberhuemer, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlantenga, Janneke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo